{"id":"1409.6716","submitter":"Romero Solha","authors":"Romero Solha","title":"Charge quantisation without magnetic poles: a topological approach to\n  electromagnetism","comments":"9 pages, 1 appendix. Signs and constants fixed","journal-ref":"Journal of Geometry and Physics, pages 57--67, volume 99, January\n  2016","doi":"10.1016/j.geomphys.2015.09.011","report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The present work provides a theoretical explanation for the quantisation of\nelectric charges, an open problem since Millikan's oil drop experiment in 1909.\nThis explanation is based solely on Maxwell's theory, it recasts\nElectromagnetic theory under the language of complex line bundles; therefore,\nneither magnetic poles nor quantum mechanics are invoked. The existence of\nmagnetic poles was essentially the only theoretical explanation for charge\nquantisation (e.g. Dirac's magnetic pole), and there is no experimental data\nsupporting their existence.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 Jun 2014 17:19:40 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 8 Aug 2015 20:49:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 28 Sep 2015 21:33:15 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sun, 1 Oct 2017 04:53:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-03"}
